Hello, all!

I have a problem exposing a class with custom operator `new` (custom allocation in a heap book).
Here is an example:

```c++
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
namespace py = pybind11;

class Example {
public:
    static void*    operator new(std::size_t size);
    static void     operator delete(void* p, std::size_t size);
    Example() {}
};

PYBIND11_MODULE(test, m) {
    m.doc() = "test";
    py::class_<Example>(m, "Example")
            .def(py::init<>())
    ;
}
```
The problem arises due to the fact that this statement
```c++
 .def(py::init<>())
```
is a shorthand for
```c++
.def("__init__", [](Example &instance) {new (&instance) Example();}
```
which results in the next error:
`
pybind11/pybind11.h:1320:60: error: no matching function for call to ‘Example::operator new(sizetype, Base*&)’
cl.def("__init__", [](Base *self_, Args... args) { new (self_) Base(args...); }, extra...);
`

It worked in Boost.Python out-of-the-box, because they have, apparently, different way of creating a constructor's bindings.

How it is possible to resolve this problem?

I am tinkering with exposing an existing dictionary with data to Python. My code is pretty simple:

```C++
#include <map>
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
#include <pybind11/stl.h>

namespace py = pybind11;

std::map<std::string, std::string> data = {
	{"key", "value"},
	{"key2", "value2"},
};

namespace {
  py::dict buildPythonDict() {
    py::dict results;

    for (const auto i: data) {
     results[py::cast(i.first)] = py::cast(i.second);
    }
    return results;
  }

  const auto py_data = buildPythonDict();
}


void expose(py::module &m) {
	m.attr("DATA") = py_data;
}
